$AAPL So, no longer breaking out units going forward. That is typically a warning sign that offerings are mature/going wrong way. As the installed base stalls, the rate of service growth slows.
Then they will get it and turn around and slash ASP, but a lot of damage will be done by then re underlying global share loss and less services because of less units! They got the strategy wrong.

The only innovation was hiking ASP and although it felt great they did it until they overdosed. Smarter strategy may have been lower ASP, more units and more global share leading to more future annuity services.
But $AAPL chose to do the quick and dirty thing over the short term instead. @TOMKEENE
Yes because they are often mature companies with little other reinvestment opportunities. $AAPL

disappointment because they introduced new phones this Q this year (and filled the channel) and not last year, so flat y-y on units is particularly bad? Seems tough to have highest mkt cap in world as a share losing company.

Also if a big part of value is growing the ecosystem and services, the poor unit growth (and share loss) should be a harbinger of slowing service growth. Seems they are making a huge mistake taking ASP up so much. Sure it is like doing a few lines of blow over the short term.

Feels great. But can only do it so long. Really is amazing their only real innovation has been to take up ASP, but some big warning signs underneath what optically looks good over short term. @realmoney

Initiated $SPY short in after hours, again. On @realmoney 'I Call B.S. on Apple Commentary' * It's no longer the economy stupid, it's China stupid! $AAPL has just issued poor guidance and will no longer report unit shipments. I watched all day the endless procession of traders

(who have no credentials in giving commentary on the company's quarter), analysts (who should know better) and money managers (who are talking their book) wax enthusiastically about Apple's quarterly prospects -- that were just announced. Most will forget their positive
narrative too often expressed with confidence. Some have asked why I am so critical of these dolts. This afternoon is yet another example. Being wrong is OK, but being smug is not.

Hide your portfolios and children from these talking heads in the business media who are trying to gain viewers or sell you a service. I call B.S. Again. Talk on your smart phone but there are better ideas in the market as the company is too reliant on China and times they are a
changin' in that part of the world. It's a region, going forward, that has become a liability and not an asset.
$AAPL" Its the Economy stupid" is going to be replaced with "its China stupid!"
